segments.text: OK. First of all, Mr. Dunn, would you tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, if you know them, where they were born, where you were born, and the schools you attended before you entered Texas A&M?
Well, my father was born in Arkansas, in Dallark.
and came to Texas and settled around near Lancaster, Texas, south of Dallas.
And at an age, when he was about 12 years old, with his father, he was orphaned at a young age and grew up on a farm in Dallas County.
went to work for the postal system and worked in the postal system until his death in 1936 at the age of 57.
My mother...
Your father's name?
My father's name was Charles Allen Dunn.
My mother was born in...
at Lavon near McKinney, Texas, Collin County, I believe.
And was a one of large, one child of a large family.
Her mother died when she was three years old and she was raised mostly by her aunt in the
Rockwall County near Dallas.
She taught school in a country school near Lancaster where she met my father and they were married in the year 1902.
I was raised in Dallas and attended the grade school and the Oak Cliff High School in Dallas before I went to A&M.
I had one brother and one sister.
My brother graduated from Texas A&M in chemical engineering, and my sister attended CIA before her marriage.
They are both deceased.
My mother and father are both deceased, and I'm the only remaining
member of the family still living.
Could you tell us what was your mother's name?
My mother's name was Charlotte Webb.
And she always told me that I was going to A&M and I didn't know there was any other school.
But when I left to go
go to college, I had $100 in my pocket and somehow managed to graduate in mechanical engineering four years later with about $1,500 in the bank.
Is that enough for the background?
You mentioned the fact that your mother had always said you were going to A&M.
I was going to ask you what factors were involved in your choice of A&M.
It looks as though your mother chose the school for you.
Well, my brother had entered A&M two years before, and I didn't know anything about any other school.

The reason my mother said I was going to A&M, she didn't know how we could pay for it, but she was so determined that I get an education that she always told me that I'd be able to work it out, which I did.
What were the procedures which you went through to enter A&M?
I don't recall anything except getting off of the H&TC train about 4 o'clock in the morning in College Station and waiting until time to go to the registration office.
In those days, I don't believe we had the formal
application and acceptance, I did have my high school record and was enrolled the day I arrived.
Then you arrived there just in time for the classes to start in the fall, I would take it.
Yes.
What were your first reactions to the college and to the community of College Station when you arrived there at 4 o'clock in the morning?
Or I guess that's kind of difficult to ask you what your reactions were at that time, but your immediate reactions to the school once you got there.
It was all very strange to me.
I'd never seen the school, although my brother had been there two years.
And it was a rather lonesome feeling.
I believe it was the farthest I'd ever been away from home.
But I immediately began to get familiar with the
habits then that were predominant.
The freshman wasn't long in finding out his place on the campus and was kept busy.
I didn't, my first trip home was for the Christmas holidays.
So during that period of time, if I had
not been as busy as I was trying to pay off the note I made with the college to enroll.
In those days, we had no student loan funds, but the college would accept your note provided you paid it all off before you enrolled the next semester.
So I went to the student labor people
obtained work at 25 cents an hour, which included cleaning out the horse barns and picking up papers and trash on the campus and chopping weeds and so forth.
And that was in the beginning before I was able to obtain a regular job.
Now, my first job
which I kept three years, was waiting on tables in the mess hall.
It paid about $20 a month in those days and almost paid for my entire expense for a college board and room.
But after that, I began to get other jobs lined up.
Were there limitations on the number of hours you could work a week?
No.
You could work any time you weren't in class.
OK.
This money which you earned, did the school pay that to you and then you repay it to the school?
Or did they just deduct it from your account that you?
They just credited to my note.
I never saw any money.
Until you didn't see anything.
You had the note all paid off then.
Yes.
OK.

Would you describe a typical day from, say, the time you got up in the morning and the procedure of getting up, approximately how many hours you spent in class a day, what you did on your other activities, and then the procedure for going to bed and what time you went to bed?
Well, of course, that varied.
I worked all of my spare time.
But the schedules were irregular.
The days you had lab work, you had more hours.
And the day you had just regular classes, you had less.
And then I had to get up around 6.30 in the morning in order to get to the mess hall.
on time in those days.
We had when you got this mess hall job was one of the most sought after employment job because it didn't take time except just before and during mealtime.
The rule was that if
As many as three of the waiters were absent at any one meal, they all lost their job.
But if one or two was absent, then they didn't lose their job.
But I couldn't take a chance on losing my job, so I was always present.
And then classes, first class would start
at 8 o'clock, and on the days that we had the lab work, why, sometimes they'd run as late as 5, with some hours off in between, some time off in between.
And then we had quarter quarters at 7.30.
And in those days, every student had to be in his room at 7.30 and could not be out for any purpose without a pass.
And this was very strict discipline administered by the upperclassmen in the dormitory.
Who could issue the pass?
Your commanding officer in the dormitory.
Your company commander.
Yeah, that...
That would be only for purposes like going to the library and other legitimate reasons.
And you were not allowed to visit other rooms.
So you either stayed in your room and studied, or you stayed in the room and looked at the walls.
What about if you needed some help from somebody on, say, a particular problem that you had to work out in a chemistry class or something?
Could you get permission to go to someone else in your class then for aid in working out the problem?
Yes.
Yes, you could.
And there was always someone available, usually an upper student, who was willing to help you.
Now, did you have...
A guard patrolling the hallways?
No, we did not have.
The reason I ask is because at one point I believe they did.
At one point, but that was before my time.
Before your time.
Okay.
Then you said you got up about 6.30 and went to the mess hall.
I take it then most of the fellow students got up after you did.
Yes, they...
I've forgotten whether breakfast is 7 or 7.30, but they had to march to the mess hall for all meals.
Each company would respond to the bugle call for getting up

call to formation and and then of course they had bugle call for call to quarters and for taps at night and after 11 o'clock your lights had to be out and they you weren't permitted except in special cases to keep them on after 11 o'clock if you had some studying that
you hadn't gotten done.
You've talked about working in the mess hall and marching there in formation.
What was the food like in the mess hall?
Well, it really wasn't bad, but you got a little tired of it, I guess, as they do even today.
But there was plenty of food, and most all students
did very well on the food because of the regular meals and sufficient amount of it.
They gained weight very rapidly and we got along well.
But there was a lot of complaining, griping about food at times because of the sameness of it.
Did you have a pretty standard menu, same each week, or each day of each week, or did they kind of alter the, if you had, did you have steak on the same day every week, or?
We never had steak, that I recall.
But they had, of course, the training tables had steak, but I didn't have access to a training table until
my junior year when I was on the cross-country team.
But I'd say that all in all the food was very good and the proof of the pudding is that the students gained weight and kept in good condition.
Well, I imagine they had plenty of physical exercise to help in keeping them in condition.
Yes, plenty of exercise.
Of course, on the drill fields and athletics and intramural activities gave everybody an opportunity to get plenty of exercise.
Of course, in those days, you walked everywhere you went.
No car was allowed on the campus.
No marriage student was allowed to attend A&M.
Everyone lived in the dormitory.
Did anybody ride a bicycle?
Yes, a few of the college professors did.
No students, though?
I don't recall any students having a bicycle.
Well, I ask that for two reasons.
Partly, today, of course, bicycles are very popular on campus, and we have an old picture or two showing the front of a dormitory that has a bicycle in it.
Well, they could have been, but they weren't predominant in those days.
What was life like in the dormitory?
Well, during the periods when there was no quarter quarters, it got pretty noisy and rough at times.
The boys amused themselves in various ways, such as finding one of their classmates asleep in bed and drowning him out by pouring water on him.
And there was a good deal of hell-raising during the hours that they weren't under restrictions.
So the hours of restriction were after 7.30 in the evening?
Yes, yes.

earlier than that say between 6 30 in the morning and 7 30 in the evening they could do pretty well as they wanted to yes and they did and they did okay what dormitories did you live in if you can remember yes i can remember i uh my freshman year i lived on the fourth stoop of old foster hall there was only about three rooms on the fourth stoop i remember the bath and the
The shower and the bathrooms were on the first floor, and so I had to go up and down those steps to take my shower and back up to my room.
But there was some advantage in living up there in the small area.
There wasn't quite as much activity.
In my sophomore year, I lived in the Bazell Hall.
Now, A&M has, at many times during its history, faced housing shortages.
In my freshman year and my sophomore year, I lived in the room with two other students, three in a room.
And then my junior year, there wasn't any housing at all in the dormitories for
some of the companies and my company, Company E Infantry, was put in army tents.
And then a few, two or three months after that, they had built the shacks, they called them.
In place of the canvas, they had built wooden shacks.
We had
wood-burning stoves with the smokestack up through the middle.
We had a light cord with a bulb on the end of it, a kitchen table, and two kitchen chairs, but only two to a shack.
Were these what was known as the Hollywood shacks?
Yes.
They were all wood then?
Not in the beginning.
There were 16-foot square army tents with a wooden floor, and then later on they built the shacks on the same floor.
At one time they all had canvas tents with, I guess, dirt floors, and then later they had some wooden walls with canvas roofs.
Well, I went through that, but never a dirt floor.
It was a...
That was about 1910, I believe.
Well, that was before my time.
But in my time, when I recall these housing situations when I was in school and I look at this beautiful dormitory that has my name on it, I see that we've come a long way.
Yes, we have.
Where did you live your senior year?
My senior year I lived in Mitchell Hall in a corner basement room.
Did you ever have any problem with bugs or anything like that in your rooms?
Well, there were some times when the bugs were discovered in some of the dormitories and then the fumigation
process took care of it.
I was wondering, because you know Charlie Crawford.
Yes.
He was telling me about a problem he had with bugs in his room at one point and measures he took to keep them out of his room.
Well, they weren't in his room.
They were in somebody's room in his company, I think.
Well, it happened on occasion while I was in school, but not in my room.
And the school took pretty immediate measures to get rid of them, I take it, as soon as they were discovered.
You mentioned earlier that the upperclassmen saw to it that you were busy and that you learned your place pretty quickly after you got there.
Could you tell us a little bit about what privileges the upperclassmen did have over the freshmen, and what things they had you freshmen do?
Well, I had the privilege of keeping three rooms in addition to my own in my freshman year.
And the upperclassmen in those days

would pick out a freshman and then you were known as their fish and of course you had a little problem in case their room did not pass room inspection as well as your own so when we got through with that breakfast before and before eight o'clock i had a very busy time of cleaning rooms
These were three upperclassmen in your company?
Yes.
Three rooms.
Three rooms.
With two and sometimes as many as three in a room.
So by keeping the room, this meant cleaning it, making up the bunk and everything?
Yes.
What else did you have to do for the upperclassmen?
Run errands.
And sometimes there were little
burdensome, but you had to be ready to go when they wanted to send out for something or take their cleaning to Charlie Nitch's cleaning shop or whatever errands were to be done.
I guess when you were there, they didn't have candy machines and soda machines quite as prolifically as they do today.
No.
When I was there, we either ate in the mess hall or at Casey's Confectionary.
There was no place to buy food off the campus, no stores.

went back and forth to Bryan when, on a few occasions, we went on the Tuna Vale Trolley, which was a little electrical railroad car, street car type thing, that was really a Tuna Vale Trolley, cost 15 cents each way, and I usually didn't have the 15 cents, and I had no reason to go to Bryan anyway.
But the...
as we had quite a bit of hazing in those days, and it was a question of learning to live with it and enjoy it, so to speak, and actually it...
served to tie you closer to the students, although it was never justified.
It was prevalent.
Would you say that sometimes the upperclassmen abused the freshmen?
Yes.
Human nature is the same wherever you find it.
And that was, I never knew of anyone getting hurt.
But it was a pretty rough treatment at times.
You indicated that if the upperclassman whose room you were keeping didn't pass inspection as well as your own, you were apt to get into trouble.
Would this involve a leather strap in any way?
Or what kind of trouble did you get into?
Usually a board.
A board.
A fish paddle?
Yeah.
We've got a couple of those fish paddles in the archives.
I think we're about at the end of this.
Let me speed it up and get to the end.
